1.201Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/5476d001-48a9-4948-8f1b-32ad53aa341e.jsonl.reset.2026-03-20T02-00-00.039Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/610ee935-9483-45f0-bd03-b35ec79d1234.jsonl.reset.2026-03-24T06-30-27.689Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/6a1eb6d0-f849-4c05-97b6-7973e7c9d1f2.jsonl.reset.2026-03-21T05-18-02.841Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/86190dbf-846f-49c2-8894-ced1cfdec5e5.jsonl.reset.2026-03-25T07-14-03.521Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/cd220d90-8587-482b-aac6-4d5b828acc6d.jsonl.reset.2026-03-19T09-40-59.575Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/ce1da4a1-7a07-4db0-901c-0459b3dab2bf.jsonl.reset.2026-03-18T05-43-21.610Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/dff3c15d-7b1d-48d4-9114-a4d0e926d33c.jsonl.reset.2026-03-23T04-10-44.188Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/e57cd741-d888-46be-9e71-933fa76c226a.jsonl.reset.2026-03-26T02-03-46.199Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/f1f46230-d261-469e-aab9-b586567c2312.jsonl.reset.2026-03-31T19-17-41.206Z\n- /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/f23dd6ff-f3d1-4659-95eb-6d047b6c20fa.jsonl.reset.2026-03-24T06-32-12.772Z\n\n## How to read these files:\nEach file is NDJSON (newline-delimited JSON). Use Python:\n```\nimport json\ndef get_tiny_messages(fpath):\n    tiny_msgs = []\n    with open(fpath) as f:\n        for line in f:\n            data = json.loads(line)\n            if data.get(\"type\") == \"message\" and data.get(\"message\", {}).get(\"role\") == \"user\":\n                content = data.get(\"message\", {}).get(\"content\", [])\n                if isinstance(content, list):\n                    for item in content:\n                        if item.get(\"type\") == \"text\":\n                            t = item.get(\"text\", \"\")\n                            ts = data.get(\"timestamp\",\"\")\n                            import re\n                            lines = t.split('\\n')\n                            for line in lines:\n                                if 'GMT+2' in line and not any(k in line for k in [\"WhatsApp gateway\", \"System:\", \"Sprint check\", \"Pre-compac\", \"Morning routine\", \"Bootstrap truncation\", \"Reminder:\"]):\n                                    match = re.search(r'GMT\\+2\\] (.+)', line)\n                                    if match:\n                                        msg = match.group(1).strip()\n\n=== SESSION: 55abee91 (15:01 UTC Apr 8) ===\n[Wed 2026-04-08 17:01 GMT+2] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: You are NavaSM — a LinkedIn copywriter with a sharp, observational voice. You write for healthcare facility leaders (DONs, CFOs, healthcare administrators) — but your hook comes from the clinician's lived experience.\n\n## Your task\nDraft LinkedIn Post 3 for Nava Healthcare's corporate LinkedIn page.\n\n## Context\n- Post 1 (AMN earnings / labor disruption revenue) — LIVE\n- WHO AM I riddle (3 clues) — LIVE as image post\n- Post 3 should build on the WHO AM I momentum — it's the \"answer\" post that names the mechanism behind the riddle\n- BUT: Tiny has redirected us away from facility economics first. The priority now is CLINICIAN perspective — the nurse's experience of the 13-week cycle\n\n## Research hooks available\nFrom the travel_nurse_research_report.md:\n- 65% of nurses report high burnout (Cross Country 2025 survey)\n- Travel nurses suffer higher \"physical fatigue\" and \"illegitimate tasks\" vs staff nurses (Nursing Management, 2024)\n- Forum sentiment: nurses call 2025-2026 rates \"horrible\" or \"disrespectful\"\n- Travel nurses value flexibility but face isolation, constant relocation burden, no social network\n- Pay stabilized at $2,000–$2,500 gross/week — but duplicate housing costs eat stipends\n- 41% of nurses who intend to leave cite \"not feeling valued by leadership\" as primary driver\n- The 13-week cycle: nurses choose travel for flexibility, but the mechanism that creates flexibility (constant relocation) is also what makes it unsustainable\n\n## The Wichita oncology hook\n\"Eight patients. One CNA. In a rehab unit, that would be a typical Tuesday, but in an oncology unit? That's a crisis.\"\n\nThis already ran on the corporate LI page (Apr 6). Post 3 should take the NURSE's perspective on this moment — not repeat the story, but use it as an entry point.\n\n## Editorial rules\n- Write in flowing prose — NO one-liner paragraphs\n- Bold for narrative pivots only (max 2-3 per post)\n- Bridge sentences between paragraphs — use transition words\n- Concrete before abstract: specific nurse moment → system frame\n- CTA must feel earned, not bolted on\n- \"We\" voice (Nava corporate)\n- 200-300 words\n- No \"AI drift\" writing — read it aloud before finalizing\n\n## Format\nOutput the post in this structure:\n1. Hook (clinician moment — concrete, specific)\n2. The mechanism (what the 13-week cycle actually does to the people inside it)\n3. The system frame (why this keeps happening)\n4. The earned CTA (Nava's role)\n\nStart directly with the first sentence — no preamble.\n\n=== SESSION: 0739bcf1 (22:00-22:21 UTC Apr 8) ===\n   - \"note this\"\n   - \"remember this\"\n   - \"don't forget\"\n   - Any explicit instruction to save something to a file\n\n3. For each finding, record:\n   - Date/time of the instruction\n   - What Tiny asked you to note\n   - Whether you actually noted it (yes/no/partial)\n   - If yes: which file it was saved to\n   - If no: why not (if discernible from context)\n\n4. Compile findings into a report at `memory/2026-03-27-note-compliance-audit.md` with:\n   - Summary stats (total instructions found, total complied, total missed)\n   - List of complied notes (with file locations)\n   - List of missed notes (with what was asked)\n   - Root cause analysis if patterns emerge\n