{"type":"message","id":"1a8506b4","parentId":"0fc0fa46","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:49:13.644Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. Skill updated, draft saved, committed (5ccf878).\n\n**What changed in the editor skill:**\n\n1. **No lore assumptions** — every post stands alone for readers who know nothing about Nava\n2. **Reveal sequencing** — evidence first, conclusion after the reader follows\n3. **Fairness** — don't universalize; acknowledge variation in human systems\n4. **Karaoke test** — the learning curve is social, not logistical\n5. **Don't state the obvious** — if the model requires something, don't explain what it requires; humanize the mechanism\n6. **Watch for repetition of key words** — \"structure\" twice signals redundancy\n7. **TinyQE cold-run only** — no corpus context\n8. **Bullets in closer only** — acceptable for 3-item Nava do-list\n9. **Punchy closer contrast** — continuity vs循环, merry-go-rounds\n\nReady to publish Post 3."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":72230,"output":229,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72459,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775738953640}}
{"type":"message","id":"ac25ebc9","parentId":"1a8506b4","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:50:24.962Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 14:50 GMT+2] Now, with your new skills, can you tell what I changed and why I changed it? If it wasn't obvious why the change needed to happen, you need to update your skill once again:\n--------------------\nA travelling nurse reaches week seven of her contract and finally understands the culture and where the best karaoke in town is. Week nine, she's started anticipating which physicians prefer which workflows.\n\nThen week thirteen arrives, and she leaves.\n\n𝗧𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝗽𝗽𝗲𝗻𝘀 𝗹𝗶𝗸𝗲 𝗰𝗹𝗼𝗰𝗸𝘄𝗼𝗿𝗸, but not because nurses want to leave. Some negotiate to come back. Some choose their next contract carefully. But many leave because this is how to make a living in this industry.\n\nThe 13-week reset is a structural feature of the travel staffing model. Agencies profit on volume: new placements, new contracts, new orientation gaps. A nurse who knows your unit intimately is a nurse who's harder to place. Familiarity breeds comfort, and places unknown come with uncertainty and social anxiety. So the system moves them before they feel at home.\n\n𝗬𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝘂𝗻𝗶𝘁 𝗽𝗮𝘆𝘀 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗽𝗿𝗶𝗰𝗲: hand-off errors, orientation costs, the institutional knowledge that never accumulates because it keeps walking out the door.\n\nWe built Nava differently. Continuity requires someone who stays, so we structure around that from day one:\n • Truth at placement, \n • Follow-up after arrival, \n • Relationships that outlast the contract cycle.\n\n𝗕𝗲𝗰𝗮𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝘄𝗲 𝗱𝗼𝗻'𝘁 𝗱𝗲𝗮𝗹 𝗶𝗻 𝟭𝟯-𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗸 𝗺𝗲𝗿𝗿𝘆-𝗴𝗼-𝗿𝗼𝘂𝗻𝗱𝘀.\n\nIf you're tired of funding the learning curve, let's talk."}],"timestamp":1775739024928}}
{"type":"message","id":"5ab7cdd5","parentId":"ac25ebc9","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:50:57.463Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Two changes:\n\n1. **\"her\" → \"them\"** — plural pronoun now matches the plural subject (the pattern of nurses, not one individual). \"Her\" was pulling back to the singular nurse story while the sentence was explaining the systemic mechanism. \"Them\" keeps both threads aligned.\n2. **\"that happens\" → \"they feel at home\"** — \"that happens\" is too vague for the emotional weight of the sentence. \"Feel at home\" is visceral, specific, and ties back to the karaoke/belonging theme. The earlier version was making an abstract structural point where it needed to land an emotional one.\n\nThe first change I would have caught. The second — \"that happens\" being too weak — I should have caught. It passed my editorial review and it shouldn't have.\n\nUpdating the skill:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_76896ea7-f978-4bf3-b5c7-1cde31ade54f","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/linkedin-writer/SKILL.md","new_string":"### 10. \"That Happens\" Is Too Weak — Be Visceral, Not Abstract\nWhen describing a pattern or mechanism, \"that happens\" is an abstract placeholder. The reader needs a concrete, emotional reality to hold onto.\n\n**Wrong:** \"So the system moves her before that happens.\"\n**Right:** \"So the system moves them before they feel at home.\"\n\n\"Feel at home\" is visceral — it names the specific thing being lost. \"That happens\" names nothing. Apply this test to every structural claim: can the reader see, feel, or imagine the thing you're describing? If not, be specific.","old_string":"### 9. The Punchy Closer Contrast"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":74227,"output":793,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75020,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775739057456}}
{"type":"message","id":"ecc44938","parentId":"5ab7cdd5","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:50:57.559Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_76896ea7-f978-4bf3-b5c7-1cde31ade54f","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/linkedin-writer/SKILL.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  69 - They're explaining what Nava does differently\n  70 \n  71 They are NOT acceptable in the post body.\n  72 \n- 73 ### 9. The Punchy Closer Contrast\n+ 73 ### 10. \"That Happens\" Is Too Weak — Be Visceral, Not Abstract\n+ 74 When describing a pattern or mechanism, \"that happens\" is an abstract placeholder. The reader needs a concrete, emotional reality to hold onto.\n+ 75 \n+ 76 **Wrong:** \"So the system moves her before that happens.\"\n+ 77 **Right:** \"So the system moves them before they feel at home.\"\n+ 78 \n+ 79 \"Feel at home\" is visceral — it names the specific thing being lost. \"That happens\" names nothing. Apply this test to every structural claim: can the reader see, feel, or imagine the thing you're describing? If not, be specific.\n  74 **End with a word that lands.** Continuity vs循环. \"Merry-go-rounds.\" The contrast should be memorable, not promotional.\n  75 \n  76 ---\n  77 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":73},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775739057527}}
