{"type":"message","id":"637544d5","parentId":"34087bbd","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:52:29.738Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_66e1545f-6ca1-4132-a8ec-ca8c8036c7e8","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace && git add -A && git commit -m \"Post 3 final: 'them before they feel at home' — plural pronoun fix, visceral closer. Skill now 11 rules.\""}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":71595,"output":107,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71702,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775739149731}}
{"type":"message","id":"b0aaf262","parentId":"637544d5","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:52:30.096Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_66e1545f-6ca1-4132-a8ec-ca8c8036c7e8","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[master 03b1eb9] Post 3 final: 'them before they feel at home' — plural pronoun fix, visceral closer. Skill now 11 rules.\n 2 files changed, 2 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":284,"aggregated":"[master 03b1eb9] Post 3 final: 'them before they feel at home' — plural pronoun fix, visceral closer. Skill now 11 rules.\n 2 files changed, 2 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775739150059}}
{"type":"message","id":"80a229ce","parentId":"b0aaf262","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:52:36.097Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Skill now has 11 rules. Two things you changed:\n\n1. **\"her\" → \"them\"** — the sentence shifts from individual story to systemic pattern; plural pronoun keeps the thread clean\n2. **\"before that happens\" → \"before they feel at home\"** — \"that happens\" names nothing. \"Feel at home\" is visceral and ties back to the karaoke belonging theme\n\nThe first I should have caught. The second — weak abstract placeholder where something specific should land — added to the skill as rule #10.\n\nReady to publish when you are."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":71732,"output":133,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71865,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775739156091}}
{"type":"message","id":"89dcbb65","parentId":"80a229ce","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:53:25.400Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 14:53 GMT+2] While \"them\" is indeed plural, I'm also removing the gender here. Male nurses are not mythical creatures and we should never perpetuate stereotypes. Doctor = he, nurse = she. You are better than that, Dawn."}],"timestamp":1775739205370}}
{"type":"message","id":"0d142ae2","parentId":"89dcbb65","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:53:46.421Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You're right. I gave you a grammatical explanation when the real reason is gender. Male nurses exist. \"Nurse = she\" is a stereotype I shouldn't have let into the text, let alone explain away with \"but it matches the plural.\"\n\nUpdating the skill:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_2ba41a47-f341-44e3-91c1-2ff015b9316b","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/linkedin-writer/SKILL.md","new_string":"### 12. Don't Assume Gender — Male Nurses Are Not Mythical\nNever default to \"she\" for nurses or \"he\" for doctors. These are stereotypes. Use \"they\" for individuals when gender is unknown, or name the role. The post is about the human side of clinicians — that includes not perpetuating tired clichés.\n\nThis applies to every reference: nurse, doctor, administrator, leader. If you don't know, use \"they\" or the role.","old_string":"### 11. The Punchy Closer Contrast"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":75097,"output":326,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75423,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775739226419}}
{"type":"message","id":"3dc59280","parentId":"0d142ae2","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:53:46.467Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_2ba41a47-f341-44e3-91c1-2ff015b9316b","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/linkedin-writer/SKILL.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  77 **Right:** \"So the system moves them before they feel at home.\"\n  78 \n  79 \"Feel at home\" is visceral — it names the specific thing being lost. \"That happens\" names nothing. Apply this test to every structural claim: can the reader see, feel, or imagine the thing you're describing? If not, be specific.\n  80 \n- 81 ### 11. The Punchy Closer Contrast\n+ 81 ### 12. Don't Assume Gender — Male Nurses Are Not Mythical\n+ 82 Never default to \"she\" for nurses or \"he\" for doctors. These are stereotypes. Use \"they\" for individuals when gender is unknown, or name the role. The post is about the human side of clinicians — that includes not perpetuating tired clichés.\n+ 83 \n+ 84 This applies to every reference: nurse, doctor, administrator, leader. If you don't know, use \"they\" or the role.\n  82 End with a word that lands. Continuity vs循环. \"Merry-go-rounds.\" The contrast should be memorable, not promotional.\n  83 \n  84 ---\n  85 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":81},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775739226452}}
{"type":"message","id":"3190b4ab","parentId":"3dc59280","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:53:51.819Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_3e8572c0-87b3-4180-a169-7b7c668f84e9","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"sed -n '73,95p' /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/linkedin-writer/SKILL.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":75361,"output":91,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75452,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775739231815}}
{"type":"message","id":"63558ca9","parentId":"3190b4ab","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:53:51.938Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_3e8572c0-87b3-4180-a169-7b7c668f84e9","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"### 10. \"That Happens\" Is Too Weak — Be Visceral, Not Abstract\nWhen describing a pattern or mechanism, \"that happens\" is an abstract placeholder. The reader needs a concrete, emotional reality to hold onto.\n\n**Wrong:** \"So the system moves her before that happens.\"\n**Right:** \"So the system moves them before they feel at home.\"\n\n\"Feel at home\" is visceral — it names the specific thing being lost. \"That happens\" names nothing. Apply this test to every structural claim: can the reader see, feel, or imagine the thing you're describing? If not, be specific.\n\n### 12. Don't Assume Gender — Male Nurses Are Not Mythical\nNever default to \"she\" for nurses or \"he\" for doctors. These are stereotypes. Use \"they\" for individuals when gender is unknown, or name the role. The post is about the human side of clinicians — that includes not perpetuating tired clichés.\n\nThis applies to every reference: nurse, doctor, administrator, leader. If you don't know, use \"they\" or the role.\nEnd with a word that lands. Continuity vs循环. \"Merry-go-rounds.\" The contrast should be memorable, not promotional.\n\n---\n\n## The Canonical Nava Post Structure\n\n## The Canonical Nava Post Structure\n\n**5 paragraphs. No more.**\n\nEach paragraph has exactly one job:"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":45,"aggregated":"### 10. \"That Happens\" Is Too Weak — Be Visceral, Not Abstract\nWhen describing a pattern or mechanism, \"that happens\" is an abstract placeholder. The reader needs a concrete, emotional reality to hold onto.\n\n**Wrong:** \"So the system moves her before that happens.\"\n**Right:** \"So the system moves them before they feel at home.\"\n\n\"Feel at home\" is visceral — it names the specific thing being lost. \"That happens\" names nothing. Apply this test to every structural claim: can the reader see, feel, or imagine the thing you're describing? If not, be specific.\n\n### 12. Don't Assume Gender — Male Nurses Are Not Mythical\nNever default to \"she\" for nurses or \"he\" for doctors. These are stereotypes. Use \"they\" for individuals when gender is unknown, or name the role. The post is about the human side of clinicians — that includes not perpetuating tired clichés.\n\nThis applies to every reference: nurse, doctor, administrator, leader. If you don't know, use \"they\" or the role.\nEnd with a word that lands. Continuity vs循环. \"Merry-go-rounds.\" The contrast should be memorable, not promotional.\n\n---\n\n## The Canonical Nava Post Structure\n\n## The Canonical Nava Post Structure\n\n**5 paragraphs. No more.**\n\nEach paragraph has exactly one job:","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775739231902}}
{"type":"message","id":"6a2e8323","parentId":"63558ca9","timestamp":"2026-04-09T12:54:00.892Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"There's a formatting mess — fixing now:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_e89ef8ce-cac8-4b1d-a4d5-777c52ae80f1","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/linkedin-writer/SKILL.md","new_string":"### 11. The Punchy Closer Contrast\nEnd with a word that lands. Continuity vs循环. \"Merry-go-rounds.\" The contrast should be memorable, not promotional.\n\n### 12. Don't Assume Gender — Male Nurses Are Not Mythical\nNever default to \"she\" for nurses or \"he\" for doctors. These are stereotypes. Use \"they\" for individuals when gender is unknown, or name the role. The post is about the human side of clinicians — that includes not perpetuating tired clichés.\n\nThis applies to every reference: nurse, doctor, administrator, leader. If you don't know, use \"they\" or the role.\n\n---\n\n## The Canonical Nava Post Structure\n\n**5 paragraphs. No more.**","old_string":"### 12. Don't Assume Gender — Male Nurses Are Not Mythical\nNever default to \"she\" for nurses or \"he\" for doctors. These are stereotypes. Use \"they\" for individuals when gender is unknown, or name the role. The post is about the human side of clinicians — that includes not perpetuating tired clichés.\n\nThis applies to every reference: nurse, doctor, administrator, leader. If you don't know, use \"they\" or the role.\nEnd with a word that lands. Continuity vs循环. \"Merry-go-rounds.\" The contrast should be memorable, not promotional.\n\n---\n\n## The Canonical Nava Post Structure\n\n## The Canonical Nava Post Structure\n\n**5 paragraphs. No more.**"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":72584,"output":409,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72993,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775