14:09 GMT+2] Sorry, my internet discontinued, please proceed, I've reconnected\\\\n- Assistant: [non-text content: toolCall]\\\\n- Tool result (exec): (no output)\\\\n- Assistant: The \\\\\\\"designed this way\\\\\\\" fix: lead with what the 13-week cycle *does* to a unit, then let the reader reach the conclusion themselves, then name it. Right now we're landing the reveal before the reader has the evidence to follow.\\\\n\\\\nRevised structure:\\\\n\\\\n1. The nurse's experience (weeks 7-9 — learning, finally knowing the room)\\\\n2. Contract ends — she's gone\\\\n3. This isn't random — it happens *every time*\\\\n4. The pattern: the 13-week reset\\\\n5. The business model: why agencies structurally can't want continuity\\\\n6. Nava's answer\\\\n\\\\nReader sees themselves in the pattern before we name it. No lore required.\\\\n\\\\n...\\\\n- User: System: [2026-04-09 14:09:48 GMT+2] WhatsApp gateway connected.\\\\n\\\\nSender (untrusted metadata):\\\\n```json\\\\n{\\\\n  \\\\\\\"label\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"gateway-client\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"openclaw-tui\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"username\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"openclaw-tui\\\\\\\"\\\\n}\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\n[Thu 2026-04-09 14:11 GMT+2] Yes, rewrite post 3\\\\n- Assistant: Here's the rewrite — reader discovers the pattern before we name it:\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\nA nurse reaches week seven of her contract and finally stops second-guessing where the supplies are kept. Week nine, she's started anticipating which physicians prefer which workflows. She's learning the room.\\\\n\\\\nThen week thirteen arrives, and she leaves.\\\\n\\\\n**It happens like clockwork.** Every contract cycle, the same moment — the nurse who's finally worth keeping is gone before she has a chance to become embedded. The learning curve costs are absorbed by the unit. The next contract brings someone new, and the cycle start...\\\\n- User: Sender (untrusted metadata):\\\\n```json\\\\n{\\\\n  \\\\\\\"label\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"gateway-client\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"openclaw-tui\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"username\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"openclaw-tui\\\\\\\"\\\\n}\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\n[Thu 2026-04-09 14:14 GMT+2] Hold on, we lost something here. I said we need to be fair about returning traavellers and some nurse autonomy - which I just assume is there. If I was a New Yorker that despised the thought of 13 weeks in texas, I'd rather volunteer at a food bank in Chicago if I can afford it before someone drags me to the south.\\\\n- Assistant: Noted. I overcorrected — the \\\\\\\"clockwork\\\\\\\" line implies every nurse leaves against their will, which is the same error in reverse.\\\\n\\\\nFix: acknowledge the nurses who *do* choose to come back, while naming the structural reality for the ones who don't.\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\nA nurse reaches week seven of her contract and finally stops second-guessing where the supplies are kept. Week nine, she's started anticipating which physicians prefer which workflows. She's learning the room.\\\\n\\\\nThen week thirteen arrives, and she leaves.\\\\n\\\\n**This happens like clockwork — but not because nurses want to leave.** Some negotiate to ...\\\",\\\"firstKeptEntryId\\\":\\\"2b2ef39e\\\",\\\"tokensBefore\\\":82632,\\\"details\\\":{\\\"readFiles\\\":[],\\\"modifiedFiles\\\":[]},\\\"fromHook\\\":true}\\n{\\\"type\\\":\\\"message\\\",\\\"id\\\":\\\"4b94522f\\\",\\\"parentId\\\":\\\"b46b9c11\\\",\\\"timestamp\\\":\\\"2026-04-09T13:03:37.946Z\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\\\\n```json\\\\n{\\\\n  \\\\\\\"message_id\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"3EB0D39967E4D484938C3B\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"sender_id\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"+27763674298\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"sender\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"+27763674298\\\\\\\"\\\\n}\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nSender (untrusted metadata):\\\\n```json\\\\n{\\\\n  \\\\\\\"label\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"+27763674298\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"+27763674298\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"e164\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"+27763674298\\\\\\\"\\\\n}\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\n*NavaSM X Draft — Results:*\\\\n\\\\n*Draft:*\\\\n> Tweet 1: They arrive knowing nothing. By week seven, they know your unit. Week thirteen, they're gone. The 13-week exit isn't random. Here's the mechanism.\\\\n>\\\\n> Tweet 2: Agencies profit on volume — new placements, new contracts, new orientation gaps. A nurse who knows your unit intimately is harder to place. Familiarity is bad for business. So they reset before comfort sets in.\\\\n>\\\\n> Tweet 3: Your unit absorbs: hand-off errors, orientation costs, and knowledge that keeps walking out the door. We built Nava differently. Follow-up that outlasts placement. Relationships that outlast the contract. Time is ticking — funding the learning curve has a cost.\\\\n\\\\n*TinyQE (cold, on text alone):*\\\\n1. *Evidence quality (high)* — claims lack data/stats. For X this is expected in 280-char bursts, but Tweet 3 especially has no anchor.\\\\n2. *Readability (medium)* — FKGL 5.5 may be too simple for healthcare executives. Tweet 3 is thudding slightly.\\\\n3. *Argumentative rigor (medium)* — needs clearer claim → evidence → reasoning chain.\\\\n\\\\n*My read:* Tweet 1 is strong. Tweet 2 is clean. Tweet 3 — \\\\\\\"funding the learning curve has a cost\\\\\\\" is abstract without a number. No stat to anchor it.\\\\n\\\\nFor X, the evidence quality flag is inherent to the format. The readable is fine for thread content.\\\\n\\\\nOptions:\\\\n1. Add a stat to Tweet 3 (orientation cost figure, turnover data) — if you have one\\\\n2. Accept as-is — thread structure works, Tweet 1 does the heavy lifting\\\\n3. Rewrite Tweet 3 for more punch\\\\n\\\\nYour call.\\\"}],\\\"timestamp\\\":1775739817932}}\\n{\\\"type\\\":\\\"message\\\",\\\"id\\\":\\\"d889eca8\\\",\\\"parentId\\\":\\\"4