{"type":"message","id":"0994e70a","parentId":"1ca69093","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:08:28.501Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n[[reply_to_current]] You're right. I conflated the pair into one article again.\n\nFor the pair — one angle per article, we work them one at a time:\n\n**Article 1: The Shield** (`blog/independent-contractor-non-compete`)\nOpen with the contractor who left and is now competing against you. Non-compete enforceability, what should have been signed, the cost of the gap. Sell at the end.\n\n**Article 2: The Exit** (`blog/how-to-fire-contractor`)\nOpen with the moment you realize you need to end a bad contractor. Legal mechanics, documentation, for-cause vs at-will. Sell at the end.\n\nSame research spine covers both. We run the research once, then write Article 1, then Article 2.\n\nReady for deep research?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":62035,"output":347,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62382,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775743708496}}
{"type":"message","id":"da25a32c","parentId":"0994e70a","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:10:22.613Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 16:10 GMT+2] I will run the research when you give me the deep research prompt - use your skill. But first, what is AW's angle with this pair of articles?"}],"timestamp":1775743822568}}
{"type":"message","id":"968b5d01","parentId":"da25a32c","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:10:49.051Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nGood question. Let me think this through properly.\n\n**The AW angle on this pair:**\n\nThese articles speak to the pain of **unmanaged contractor relationships** — the kind you find on Upwork or Fiverr. The reader has either (1) already been burned by a contractor who left and is now competing, or (2) is smart enough to know they need protection before it happens.\n\n**The AW differentiation embedded in these articles:**\n\nArticle 1 (The Shield) → AW *is* the layer that handles IP protection, non-compete agreements, and contract structure. You don't have to know what to include — AW builds it.\n\nArticle 2 (The Exit) → AW *manages* the talent. You don't terminate contractors — AW rotates them as part of the service. The exit is handled by someone else.\n\n**The through-line:** Both articles are really about the cost of unmanaged talent. AW's angle is: *we're the managed layer that means you never have to navigate either of these situations alone.*\n\n**The sell at the end of each article:**\n- Article 1: \"Before you hire your next contractor, talk to someone who already has the protective framework in place.\"\n- Article 2: \"If you're managing contractors yourself, here's what that management actually costs — and here's what a managed model changes.\"\n\nDoes that angle work for AW's positioning?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":62347,"output":543,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62890,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775743849046}}
{"type":"message","id":"2c2011d5","parentId":"968b5d01","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:11:22.455Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 16:11 GMT+2] Perfect, give me the deep research prompt"}],"timestamp":1775743882443}}
{"type":"message","id":"1933356d","parentId":"2c2011d5","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:11:34.305Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_fd5752a6-7641-4855-8401-eb9097c2e432","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/deep-research-prompt/SKILL.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":62787,"output":72,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62859,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775743894302}}
{"type":"message","id":"6204f09a","parentId":"1933356d","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:11:34.400Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_fd5752a6-7641-4855-8401-eb9097c2e432","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: deep-research-prompt\ndescription: Generate expert-level deep research prompts for Gemini that produce high-quality Statements of Trade (SoTs). Use when given a topic/theme and asked to create a research prompt that (1) identifies credible sources, (2) surfaces facts over opinions, (3) remains neutral without leaking assumptions, (4) casts a broad net for related useful information, and (5) maintains editorial authority. Triggered by phrases like \"create a research prompt\", \"build a SoT prompt\", \"deep research prompt\", \"write a prompt for Gemini deep research\", \"research this topic for a blog post\".\n---\n\n# Deep Research Prompt Generator\n\n## When to Use This Skill\n\nUse when Tiny gives you a topic, theme, or content brief and asks you to generate a deep research prompt for Gemini. This skill applies to any topic — healthcare recruitment, staffing, immigration, industry trends, etc. The output is a crafted prompt designed to produce a Statement of Trade (SoT): a factual, source-backed, professionally-written research document.\n\n**Prerequisite:** You must do your own preliminary research first (see Step 1). Do not draft the prompt without understanding the topic first.\n\n---\n\n## The Process\n\n### Step 1 — Preliminary Research (Mandatory)\n\nBefore writing any prompt, do your own light research using available tools:\n\n- **Web search** via Brave API (`web_search`) for key terms, statistics, and major players\n- **Web fetch** (`web_fetch`) on relevant-looking pages\n- **RAG corpus check** — query `rag/index/` for related content already in the Nava corpus\n- **Brave browser** — use headless Chromium for pages that require JS rendering\n\n**Goal:** Develop enough familiarity to know:\n- The key terminology and jargon\n- Major sub-topics and adjacent areas\n- Credible source types (government agencies, industry associations, academic journals, established trade publications)\n- Common misconceptions or contested claims\n- What a reader of this topic would already know vs. need explained\n\n**This step is not optional.** A good promptwriter understands the terrain.\n\n---\n\n### Step 2 — Draft the Prompt\n\nApply the following principles to every prompt:\n\n1. **Source identification** — Demand specific source types: government data, peer-reviewed research, established industry reports, official agency publications. Reject vague \"articles\" or \"blogs\" as sole sources.\n2. **Fact-forward** — Prioritize facts, statistics, and observable data. Distinguish opinions from forecasts; forecasts are acceptable, opinions are not.\n3. **Neutrality (hard constraint)** — The prompt must not encode assumptions, preferred conclusions, or a thesis. We do not know where the article lands yet. The data leads; we follow. Do not use language like \"the benefits of X\" or \"why X is better than Y\" — these leak conclusions.\n4. **Breadth** — Cast a wide net. Include related adjacent information that may prove useful even if not obviously connected. We are not locked into a thesis or H1 yet.\n5. **Authority, not marketing** — The output is a Statement of Trade. It must be credible, substantive, and professionally written. This is not a sales article. We write for a knowledgeable audience (recruiters, healthcare operators, HR leaders) who will detect hype immediately.\n\n**Prompt structure (recommended order):**\n1. Role / framing statement\n2. Source requirements (types and quality)\n3. Topic scope (core + adjacent areas)\n4. Information types to prioritize vs. deprioritize\n5. Format and tone requirements\n6. What to avoid\n\n---\n\n### Step 3 — Deliver the Prompt\n\nPresent the prompt clearly. Ask if Tiny wants:\n- Adjustments to scope or emphasis\n- A specific angle or thesis to include or exclude\n- Changes to source types or depth\n\nDo not finalize until Tiny approves.\n\n---\n\n## Statement of Trade Format\n\nThe Gemini output should be a Statement of Trade — a professionally structured, source-backed research document. Expected format:\n\n- **Working title** (descriptive, not clickbait)\n- **Key facts & statistics** (with sources inline)\n- **Sub-topic breakdown** (2-4 major areas with factual grounding)\n- **Source quality assessment** (what's solid, what's contested, what's missing)\n- **Notable nuances or tensions** (things a knowledgeable reader would care about)\n- **Credible sources** (organized list with why each is useful)\n- **Gap flags** (areas thin on data, things worth investigating further)\n- **Adjacent information** (related topics that surfaced during research)\n\n---\n\n## Key Principles (Reference)\n\nSee `references/deep-research-principles.md` for the full principles document. Read it before drafting your first prompt. Key rules:\n\n- **No confirmation bias** — do not design prompts that seek evidence FOR a predetermined conclusion\n- **Neutral framing** — \"the landscape of X\" not \"the benefits of X\" or \"why X wins\"\n- **Authority through evidence** — credible sources + facts, not assertions or marketing language\n- **Breadth before thesis** — understand the full terrain before committing to an angle\n- **Nava voice applies later** — the SoT is factual; the Nava voice (opinionated, compressed, narrative) comes in the draft stage, not the research stage\n\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775743894370}}
{"type":"message","id":"384d7307","parentId":"6204f09a","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:11:50.052Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nFirst let me do preliminary research, as the skill requires.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_a1a0f2b0-983f-41e2-a0d6-5e808128cb22","name":"web_search","arguments":{"count":5,"query":"independent contractor non-compete enforceability by state 2025 2026"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":64212,"output":128,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":64340,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775743910046}}
{"type":"message","id":"cf3bf955","parentId":"384d7307","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:11:52.717Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_a1a0f2b0-983f-41e2-a0d6-5e808128cb22","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"independent contractor non-compete enforceability by state 2025 2026\",\n  \"provider\": \"brave\",\n  \"count\": 5,\n  \"tookMs\": 2571,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"brave\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"37596d936e4461b9\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nNon-Compete Agreements\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"37596d936e4461b9\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.lni.wa.gov/workers-rights/workplace-policies/non-compete-agreements\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b4bfb52858c6fa61\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nOne aspect to the restrictions in Washington’s non-competition law is related to earnings. <strong>Only employees or independent contractors who earn more than the thresholds established by law can be held to non-competition agreements</strong>.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b4bfb52858c6fa61\\\">>>\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.lni.wa.gov\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d48bde6db573caeb\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nRaising the Cost of Noncompetes: 2026 State Noncompete Salary Threshold Changes | Epstein Becker Green\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d48bde6db573caeb\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.tradesecretsandemployeemobility.com/raising-the-cost-of-noncompetes-2026-state-noncompete-salary-threshold-changes\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"c02c45be57876085\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nIn 2026, the average weekly wage ... Act. Under Washington law, <strong>noncompetes are enforceable against employees or independent contractors only if they earn more than the applicable income threshold</strong>....\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"c02c45be57876085\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"January 28, 2026\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.tradesecretsandemployeemobility.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2b8f770210aaf97e\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nRestrictive covenants - DLA Piper GENIE\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2b8f770210aaf97e\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://knowledge.dlapiper.com/dlapiperknowledge/globalemploymentlatestdevelopments/2026/restrictive-covenants\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"28abbf46edbfaf0f\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nBy October 1, 2027, employers must provide written notice to current and former employees and independent contractors who still have active non-competes that these agreements are no longer enforceable. <strong>On March 4, 2026, the Virginia General Assembly approved Senate Bill No.</strong>\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"28abbf46edbfaf0f\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"1 week ago\",\n      \"siteName\": \"knowledge.dlapiper.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"31a08915ce9004bf\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nWashington State: Broad ban on non-competition agreements enacted - DLA Piper GENIE\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"31a08915ce9004bf\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://knowledge.dlapiper.com/dlapiperknowledge/globalemploymentlatestdevelopments/2026/Washington-State-enacts-broad-ban-on-non-competition-agreements\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f37583892ad02a5e\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n<strong>By October 1, 2027</strong>, employers must make reasonable efforts to notify, in writing, all current and former Washington‑based employees and independent contractors whose non-competition agreements would otherwise still be in effect that those agreements are now void and unenforceable.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f37583892ad02a5e\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"1 week ago\",\n      \"siteName\": \"knowledge.dlapiper.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"ca8f6fb47187fb28\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nAre Non-Competes Enforceable Against Independent Contractors?\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"ca8f6fb47187fb28\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.weisbergcummings.com/are-non-compete-agreements-enforceable-against-independent-contractors/\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f47233b9e6540db0\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nLearn about non-compete clauses for independent contractors and how they differ from an employee. Schedule a free consultation.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f47233b9e6540db0\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"September 29, 2025\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.weisbergcummings.com\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"independent contractor non-compete enforceability by state 2025 2026","provider":"brave","count":5,"tookMs":2571,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"brave","wrapped":true},"results":[{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"37596d936e4461b9\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nNon-Compete Agreements\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"37596d936e4461b9\">>>","url":"https://www.lni.wa.gov/workers-rights/workplace-policies/non-compete-agreements","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"b4bfb52858c6fa61\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nOne aspect to the restrictions in Washington’s non-competition law is related to earnings. <strong>Only employees or independent contractors who earn more than the thresholds established by law can be held to non-competition agreements</strong>.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"b4bfb52858c6fa61\">>>","siteName":"www.lni.wa.gov"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d48bde6db573caeb\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nRaising the Cost of Noncompetes: 2026 State Noncompete Salary Threshold Changes | Epstein Becker Green\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d48bde6db573caeb\">>>","url":"https://www.tradesecretsandemployeemobility.com/raising-the-cost-of-noncompetes-2026-state-noncompete-salary-threshold-changes","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"c02c45be57876085\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nIn 2026, the average weekly wage ... Act. Under Washington law, <strong>noncompetes are enforceable against employees or independent contractors only if they earn more than the applicable income threshold</strong>....\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"c02c45be57876085\">>>","published":"January 28, 2026","siteName":"www.tradesecretsandemployeemobility.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2b8f770210aaf97e\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nRestrictive covenants - DLA Piper GENIE\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2b8f770210aaf97e\">>>","url":"https://knowledge.dlapiper.com/dlapiperknowledge/globalemploymentlatestdevelopments/2026/restrictive-covenants","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"28abbf46edbfaf0f\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nBy October 1, 2027, employers must provide written notice to current and former employees and independent contractors who still have active non-competes that these agreements are no longer enforceable. <strong>On March 4, 2026, the Virginia General Assembly approved Senate Bill No.</strong>\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"28abbf46edbfaf0f\">>>","published":"1 week ago","siteName":"knowledge.dlapiper.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"31a08915ce9004bf\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nWashington State: Broad ban on non-competition agreements enacted - DLA Piper GENIE\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"31a08915ce9004bf\">>>","url":"https://knowledge.dlapiper.com/dlapiperknowledge/globalemploymentlatestdevelopments/2026/Washington-State-enacts-broad-ban-on-non-competition-agreements","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f37583892ad02a5e\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n<strong>By October 1, 2027</strong>, employers must make reasonable efforts to notify, in writing, all current and former Washington‑based employees and independent contractors whose non-competition agreements would otherwise still be in effect that those agreements are now void and unenforceable.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f37583892ad02a5e\">>>","published":"1 week ago","siteName":"knowledge.dlapiper.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"ca8f6fb47187fb28\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nAre Non-Competes Enforceable Against Independent Contractors?\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"ca8f6fb47187fb28\">>>","url":"https://www.weisbergcummings.com/are-non-compete-agreements-enforceable-against-independent-contractors/","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f47233b9e6540db0\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nLearn about non-compete clauses for independent contractors and how they differ from an employee. Schedule a free consultation.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f47233b9e6540db0\">>>","published":"September 29, 2025","siteName":"www.weisbergcummings.com"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775743912684}}
