{"type":"message","id":"2f9fc479","parentId":"4fca1377","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:12:04.354Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_a2661d3f-63e0-41da-98e4-f9ba73d7ef18","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"how to terminate independent contractor agreement legal requirements documentation\",\n  \"provider\": \"brave\",\n  \"count\": 5,\n  \"tookMs\": 4651,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"brave\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"5592cda949186af1\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nCheck out this article...How to Terminate an Independent Contractor Agreement Legally\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"5592cda949186af1\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.upcounsel.com/how-to-break-a-contract-with-a-contractor\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2a57fcacb90bbaff\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nA well-drafted independent contractor agreement should include a detailed termination clause specifying: <strong>Grounds for Termination – Clearly state what constitutes a breach of contract or under what conditions termination is allowed</strong>.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2a57fcacb90bbaff\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"May 8, 2025\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.upcounsel.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2902f3c95ca9e938\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nTerminating an Independent Contractor: How to Do it Compliantly\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2902f3c95ca9e938\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.deel.com/blog/terminating-an-independent-contractor/\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e52125e8ab866cf3\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nIf your independent contractor agreement includes notice provision, <strong>give the contractual notice of termination to the independent contractor in writing</strong>–your contract may even require that you give notice via email.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e52125e8ab866cf3\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"1 week ago\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.deel.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fd62f1d2ecbd1c5f\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nHow Does A Company Properly Terminate Independent Contractors? - Wessels Sherman\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fd62f1d2ecbd1c5f\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.wesselssherman.com/how-does-a-company-properly-terminate-independent-contractors/\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d79fda6734bd0c54\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nAdditionally, independent contractor agreements frequently have notice provisions under which <strong>a certain number of days or weeks notice must be given by the terminating party to legally terminate the agreement</strong>.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"d79fda6734bd0c54\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"September 17, 2020\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.wesselssherman.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"4628eeb0d977cf25\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nHow to Terminate an Independent Contractor Agreement\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"4628eeb0d977cf25\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.getontop.com/blog/terminate-independent-contractor-agreement\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2811d9b8bf632d7f\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nThinking about terminating a contractor agreement? This guide walks you through the process, covering valid reasons, notice periods, payments, protecting IP, and maintaining positive relationships. Terminate smoothly and legally!\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2811d9b8bf632d7f\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"January 9, 2026\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.getontop.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"c093bb204dc8dbf1\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nHow to Compliantly Terminate an Independent Contractor\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"c093bb204dc8dbf1\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.remofirst.com/post/terminate-independent-contractor-compliantly\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e4bdae2b52955561\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nYour first step in any termination process should be <strong>a thorough review of the independent contractor agreement</strong>. Ideally, your business included critical information about how the relationship can be ended in the contract.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e4bdae2b52955561\\\">>>\",\n      \"published\": \"June 6, 2025\",\n      \"siteName\": \"www.remofirst.com\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"how to terminate independent contractor agreement legal requirements documentation","provider":"brave","count":5,"tookMs":4651,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"brave","wrapped":true},"results":[{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"5592cda949186af1\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nCheck out this article...How to Terminate an Independent Contractor Agreement Legally\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"5592cda949186af1\">>>","url":"https://www.upcounsel.com/how-to-break-a-contract-with-a-contractor","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2a57fcacb90bbaff\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nA well-drafted independent contractor agreement should include a detailed termination clause specifying: <strong>Grounds for Termination – Clearly state what constitutes a breach of contract or under what conditions termination is allowed</strong>.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2a57fcacb90bbaff\">>>","published":"May 8, 2025","siteName":"www.upcounsel.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2902f3c95ca9e938\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nTerminating an Independent Contractor: How to Do it Compliantly\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2902f3c95ca9e938\">>>","url":"https://www.deel.com/blog/terminating-an-independent-contractor/","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"e52125e8ab866cf3\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nIf your independent contractor agreement includes notice provision, <strong>give the contractual notice of termination to the independent contractor in writing</strong>–your contract may even require that you give notice via email.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"e52125e8ab866cf3\">>>","published":"1 week ago","siteName":"www.deel.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fd62f1d2ecbd1c5f\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nHow Does A Company Properly Terminate Independent Contractors? - Wessels Sherman\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fd62f1d2ecbd1c5f\">>>","url":"https://www.wesselssherman.com/how-does-a-company-properly-terminate-independent-contractors/","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d79fda6734bd0c54\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nAdditionally, independent contractor agreements frequently have notice provisions under which <strong>a certain number of days or weeks notice must be given by the terminating party to legally terminate the agreement</strong>.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"d79fda6734bd0c54\">>>","published":"September 17, 2020","siteName":"www.wesselssherman.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"4628eeb0d977cf25\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nHow to Terminate an Independent Contractor Agreement\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"4628eeb0d977cf25\">>>","url":"https://www.getontop.com/blog/terminate-independent-contractor-agreement","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2811d9b8bf632d7f\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nThinking about terminating a contractor agreement? This guide walks you through the process, covering valid reasons, notice periods, payments, protecting IP, and maintaining positive relationships. Terminate smoothly and legally!\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2811d9b8bf632d7f\">>>","published":"January 9, 2026","siteName":"www.getontop.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"c093bb204dc8dbf1\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nHow to Compliantly Terminate an Independent Contractor\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"c093bb204dc8dbf1\">>>","url":"https://www.remofirst.com/post/terminate-independent-contractor-compliantly","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"e4bdae2b52955561\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nYour first step in any termination process should be <strong>a thorough review of the independent contractor agreement</strong>. Ideally, your business included critical information about how the relationship can be ended in the contract.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"e4bdae2b52955561\">>>","published":"June 6, 2025","siteName":"www.remofirst.com"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775743924332}}
{"type":"message","id":"500678d0","parentId":"2f9fc479","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:13:05.021Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nHere's the deep research prompt for this pair:\n\n---\n\n**Deep Research Prompt — Contractor Termination + Non-Compete (AW Articles 1 & 2)**\n\nYou are producing a Statement of Trade (SoT) for two related blog articles aimed at US business owners and operators who hire or manage independent contractors. The research must cover both topics with sufficient depth to write two standalone, factual, professionally written articles.\n\n**Working Titles:**\n- Article 1: \"Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements: What US Business Owners Need to Know Before They Hire\"\n- Article 2: \"How to Terminate an Independent Contractor: A Legal and Operational Guide\"\n\n**Research Goals:**\n\n1. **Non-Compete Enforceability Landscape**\n   - Current state-by-state enforceability for independent contractors specifically (note: many state laws distinguish between employees and ICs; be precise about which applies to ICs)\n   - States with active bans or strong restrictions: California (near-total ban), North Dakota, Minnesota (recent bans)\n   - States with income/earnings thresholds that gate enforceability against ICs (Washington's threshold framework as a model)\n   - States where non-competes with ICs are routinely enforced\n   - Federal status: FTC's attempted non-compete ban — what happened after the August 2024 federal court ruling; current litigation status\n   - The \"employee vs. independent contractor\" classification impact on enforceability — why classification matters for non-competes\n\n2. **What Makes a Non-Compete Agreement Legally Valid**\n   - Reasonable geographic scope, time limitation, and scope of activity — the three-part reasonableness test\n   - Trade secret and confidential information protection as a separate (and stronger) legal basis — what a legitimate non-compete actually protects vs. what it can't protect\n   - Choice of law and venue clauses — how businesses use these to select favorable state law\n   - What courts have found unreasonable in IC non-competes specifically\n\n3. **The Independent Contractor Termination Process**\n   - Contract review as first step: what the agreement says about termination (notice periods, for-cause vs at-will language, payment obligations)\n   - Written notice requirements — what constitutes legally sufficient notice\n   - For-cause termination: what constitutes a material breach sufficient to terminate without notice\n   - At-will termination: what risk it creates absent a written agreement\n   - Payment and final invoice obligations upon termination\n   - IP assignment: importance of IP clauses being in place before termination — what happens to work product created during the engagement\n\n4. **The Cost of Getting It Wrong**\n   - Breach of contract exposure from improper termination\n   - Trade secret misappropriation claims when departing contractors compete\n   - What \"inevitable disclosure\" doctrine means and which states recognize it\n   - The litigation cost landscape for contractor disputes\n\n5. **What Managed Solutions Provide**\n   - How EOR/managed staffing providers structure contracts to eliminate this exposure for clients\n   - Whether AWAA or similar managed models explicitly address IP protection and non-compete compliance in their service agreements\n\n**Source Requirements:**\n- Primary: government sources (DOL, state labor departments, courts of appeals)\n- Secondary: law firm client alerts (Epstein Becker Green, Duane Morris, Littler Mendelson — all publish regularly on this)\n- Tertiary: PEO/EOR provider blogs (Deel, Rippling, Remote) — useful for operational specifics, note where they differ from legal analysis\n- Do NOT rely on self-published \"legal guides\" from unconnected blogs as primary sources\n\n**What to prioritize:**\n- Concrete data: number of states banning IC non-competes, average enforceability threshold amounts, specific court cases with outcomes\n- Operational specifics: what notice period lengths are standard, what IP clauses actually say in practice\n- Geographic nuance: the California/Federal/national picture and why it matters for any business operating across state lines\n\n**What to avoid:**\n- Marketing language from HR tech or staffing platforms\n- Generalizations about \"non-competes\" that don't distinguish employee vs. IC rules\n- Predictions about pending legislation — report what exists, not what might pass\n\n**Format:**\nStructure the SoT as:\n1. Working title + core tension (what a reader would most want to know before reading)\n2. Key facts and statistics (with inline sources)\n3. Sub-topic breakdown covering each of the 5 research goals above\n4. Source quality assessment (solid/contested/thin) for each sub-topic\n5. Notable nuances — things a knowledgeable business operator would care about\n6. Credible source list organized by why each is useful\n7. Gap flags — areas where data is thin or contested\n\n**Tone:**\nAuthoritative, factual, substantive. This audience has been burned or is smart enough not to be. No hype. No \"empowering your team.\" Let the facts carry the weight.\n\n---\n\nRun this through Gemini deep research and come back with the SoT. Tiny will want to see the key facts and source quality assessment before we draft."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":67011,"output":1250,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":68261,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775743985009}}
{"type":"message","id":"c1ced75a","parentId":"500678d0","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:15:34.164Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 16:15 GMT+2] Hold on, how are you including language like \"SoT\" and assuming that Gemini knows what AWAA is? Also, the purpose of deep research is to ask the appropriate questions, and it will give you a complete report, no need to discuss tone, or audience. This is for our internal use!"}],"timestamp":1775744134130}}
{"type":"message","id":"159ba7e8","parentId":"c1ced75a","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:16:27.717Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n[[reply_to_current]] Right. I over-specified.\n\nThe prompt should be: the topic, the sub-questions, the source types. That's it. Nothing about format, tone, or audience — and I need to define AWAA if I'm going to mention it.\n\nHere's the corrected version:\n\n---\n\n**Deep Research Prompt — Contractor Termination + Non-Compete (Internal Research)**\n\nYou are researching two related topics for blog articles aimed at US business owners who hire independent contractors.\n\n**Topic 1 — Non-Compete Agreements with Independent Contractors**\n- State-by-state enforceability for ICs specifically (not employees) — which states ban or restrict, which routinely enforce\n- Income/threshold gating (Washington model) — how it works, which states have similar frameworks\n- The FTC non-compete ban attempt — current status after the federal court ruling\n- Why IC classification matters for enforceability\n- What makes an IC non-compete legally valid: reasonableness test (geography, time, scope)\n- Trade secret and confidential information protection as a separate legal basis\n- What courts have found unreasonable in IC non-competes specifically\n\n**Topic 2 — Independent Contractor Termination**\n- What written agreements should specify about termination (notice periods, for-cause vs at-will, payment obligations)\n- For-cause termination: what constitutes material breach\n- At-will termination risk absent a written agreement\n- IP assignment and work product — what happens when a contractor leaves\n- Payment and final invoice obligations on termination\n\n**What to surface:**\n- Concrete data: number of states, specific threshold amounts, case outcomes\n- Operational specifics: standard notice periods, what IP clauses cover in practice\n- What EOR/managed staffing providers do differently\n\n**Source types:** DOL, state labor departments, law firm client alerts (Epstein Becker Green, Littler Mendelson), PEO/EOR operational guides (Deel, Rippling). Government and legal sources primary.\n\n---\n\nThat's the research brief. Gemini produces the report, I use it to draft. Does this look right?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":68521,"output":631,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":69152,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775744187705}}
{"type":"message","id":"7162f3a0","parentId":"159ba7e8","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:17:43.590Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 16:17 GMT+2] Remember this shouldn't be confined to the US only, even though the US should probably be a focus. We are addressing international contractors also."}],"timestamp":1775744263553}}
{"type":"message","id":"9fd3b226","parentId":"7162f3a0","timestamp":"2026-04-09T14:18:06.253Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n[[reply_to_current]] Good catch. Let me fix that:\n\n---\n\n**Deep Research Prompt — Contractor Termination + Non-Compete (Internal Research)**\n\nYou are researching two related topics for blog articles aimed at business owners and operators who hire independent contractors internationally — US market is the primary focus but international dimensions matter.\n\n**Topic 1 — Non-Compete Agreements with Independent Contractors**\n- State-by-state enforceability for ICs in the US (which states ban/restrict, which enforce)\n- Why IC classification matters for enforceability — US common law vs. IRS reclassification risk\n- What makes an IC non-compete legally valid: reasonableness test (geography, time, scope)\n- Trade secret and confidential information protection as a separate, stronger legal basis\n- How non-competes work for contractors in the UK, EU, Australia, Canada — key jurisdictional differences\n- Cross-border angle: US company hiring a UK or EU contractor — which law governs, which jurisdiction applies\n- What courts have found unreasonable in IC non-competes specifically\n\n**Topic 2 — Independent Contractor Termination**\n- What written agreements should specify: notice periods, for-cause vs at-will, payment obligations, IP assignment\n- For-cause termination: what constitutes material breach under common law\n- IP assignment — work product created during the engagement, who owns it on departure\n- Payment and final invoice obligations when a contractor leaves\n- How termination of international contractors differs — tax implications, EOR obligations, jurisdiction\n- What EOR/managed staffing providers handle differently vs. direct hire\n\n**What to surface:**\n- Concrete data: state-level breakdowns, threshold amounts, case outcomes\n- International specifics: countries with near-total bans (UK, Australia), countries where non-competes with ICs are routinely enforced\n- Cross-border mechanics: choice of law, jurisdiction selection, tax withholding obligations\n- What managed solutions do differently — EOR/managed staffing provider perspective\n\n**Source types:** DOL, state labor departments, law firm client alerts (Ep Epstein Becker Green, Littler Mendelson), UK gov (GOV.UK), EU employment law sources, Australia Fair Work Commission, PEO/EOR operational guides (Deel, Rippling, Remote). Government and legal sources primary.\n\n---\n\nThat's the scope. US strong, international covered, no over-specification on format or tone. Good to run?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":69118,"output":560,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":69678,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775744286246}}
