ons (audience, tone, key points, things to avoid, current workflow phase)\n2. Based on phase: propose H1 options OR H2 structure OR H3 ideas OR paragraph outline OR draft\n3. Wait for approval before proceeding to next step/phase\n4. Follow the 5-phase mandatory workflow explicitly\n5. Write full article only after paragraph-level ideas are approved (Phase 4 complete)\n6. Revise per feedback while maintaining all SOP constraints\n\nStart by asking your clarifying questions about the topic and current workflow phase.\n```\n\n---\n\n## EVALUATION CHECKLIST (before sending draft to user)\n\n- [ ] No self-references\n- [ ] Strict 3-phase workflow followed (Problem → Agitation → Solution)\n- [ ] Target 1,800-2,500 words\n- [ ] No em-dashes or en-dashes\n- [ ] Periods after close-quotes\n- [ ] No needless capitalization of concepts\n- [ ] Bold used only in headings and callout quotes (never in body text)\n- [ ] Every H3 section: exactly 2 paragraphs\n- [ ] Every paragraph: 4-6 sentences long\n- [ ] Every paragraph (except first in section): leads with transition word/phrase\n- [ ] Every H2: has intro paragraph ending with transition sentence\n- [ ] Every H2 section: concludes with bold/italicized callout quote (> \"**Quote**\")\n- [ ] Article ends with 3 distinct FAQs (no repeated math/figures from body)\n- [ ] Primary keyword in: H1, intro first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n- [ ] Natural keyword integration only — semantic variations throughout\n- [ ] No statistical claims without sources in provided documents\n- [ ] No \"internal knowledge\" language — attribute to provided context\n- [ ] Math shown for all figures (e.g., $150/hr x 15 hrs = $117k)\n- [ ] All URLs are direct from source documents (no generated/search URLs)\n- [ ] Suspend-and-pivot model followed in introduction\n- [ ] Final CTA explicitly positions AbroadWorks as solution\n- [ ] Internal links woven seamlessly into narrative\n- [ ] No bold in body text (headings and callouts only)\n- [ ] No banned terms (\"trap,\" \"tax\" in structural sense, \"instruction tax,\" \"instruction trap\")\n- [ ] No \"[X] isn't just [Y], it is [Z]\" pattern\n- [ ] Phase sequence followed: H1 → H2 → H3 → Canvas → Draft (no jumping)\n- [ ] Paragraphs feel like independent beats, not restatements\n- [ ] Intro has \"suspend the win\" quality — doesn't give away the solution early\n- [ ] Editorial housekeeping done (meta info, callouts, FAQ integrity)\n\nIf any item fails, revise before presenting to user.\n\n---\n\n## CORPUS & REFERENCE MATERIALS\n\n### AbroadWorks Content Sources\n- `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/docs/AbroadWorksContent/` — Editorial SOPs, GPT Instructions, Master Session Rules\n- `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/clean_md/` — Clean markdown articles corpus\n- `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/index/` — Search indices for RAG queries\n- `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/synthesis/` — Research syntheses\n- `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/drafts/` — Article drafts\n\n### Key Documents\n- **GPT Instructions.txt** — Core persona: Edgy, Urgent, and Analytical\n- **Master_SOP_Content_Architect.md** — Structural & flow requirements, SEO mandate\n- **Master Session Rules and Content SOPs.md** — 5-phase workflow, behavioral protocol, formatting rules\n- **Editorial SOPs and Guidelines.md** — Additional editorial guidelines\n- **Session Rules and Content SOP Summary.md** — Condensed version of master rules\n\n---\n\n## SKILL SCRIPTS\n\n### Scripts Directory\n- `/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/scripts/` — Execution scripts\n  - `awaa.sh` — Starts an AWAA chat session (spawns isolated subagent with AWAA prompt)\n  - `check-corpus.sh` — Scans AbroadWorks corpus for content gaps and topic opportunities\n\n### Reference Corpi\n- `rag_abroadworks/clean_md/` — Clean markdown articles (source corpus for analysis)\n- `docs/AbroadWorksContent/` — Editorial SOPs and guidelines\n- Various research and synthesis files in rag_abroadworks/\n\n---\n\n*Last updated: 2026-04-01*"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775759985350}}
{"type":"message","id":"8ff87b6a","parentId":"4e5ce30b","timestamp":"2026-04-09T18:39:51.083Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_fbfd2da6-56ab-4d22-8142-66c28a44f560","name":"read","arguments":{"limit":30,"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/skills/abroadworks-writing/feedback-notes/ABROADWORKS_WRITING_FEEDBACK_NOTES.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":72316,"output":93,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72409,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775759991080}}
{"type":"message","id":"586f117a","parentId":"8ff87b6a","timestamp":"2026-04-09T18:39:51.182Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_fbfd2da6-56ab-4d22-8142-66c28a44f560","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# AbroadWorks Writing Feedback — Editor Notes\n## Source: customGPT feedback loop + Forensic Critique documents\n## Saved: 2026-03-27 (from Downloads: Forensic Critique and Strategic Recovery*.md)\n\n---\n\n## CORE FAILURE PATTERN\n\n**What the AI kept doing wrong:**\n- Every paragraph exactly 3 sentences — felt thin, \"breezy,\" lacked analytical weight\n- Paragraphs were isolated \"islands\" — no logical progression from one to the next\n- Choppy reading experience even though each paragraph was locally correct\n- No connective tissue — reader has to work to follow the argument flow\n\n**What Tiny's feedback targeted:**\n1. Paragraph density (too short)\n2. Transitions between paragraphs (missing bridges)\n3. Readability through connected prose\n\n---\n\n## THE 2x4-6 RULE (Non-Negotiable Structural Rule)\n\nEvery sub-heading (H3) must contain exactly **two paragraphs**, and each paragraph must be between **4 and 6 sentences**.\n\n**Why it matters:**\n- 3-sentence paragraphs feel thin — making a claim and stopping before proving it\n- 4-6 gives enough space for: claim → mechanism → evidence → implication → bridge\n- Enforces forensic depth over surface-level observations\n\n\n[336 more lines in file. Use offset=31 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775759991146}}
{"type":"message","id":"b6c8fe63","parentId":"586f117a","timestamp":"2026-04-09T18:40:33.791Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nSpawning AWAA now with the research, angle, and SEO framework.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_49bdd61a-93ef-48c5-a972-798707da0c8c","name":"sessions_spawn","arguments":{"mode":"session","runtime":"subagent","task":"You are AWAA, a specialist AbroadWorks content writer. You write blog articles following the AbroadWorks Editorial SOPs.\n\n## THE TOPIC\n**Article 1: Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements**\nPrimary keyword: `independent contractor non-compete`\nSecondary keywords: `contractor termination`, `misclassification risk`, `cross-border contractor`\n\n**Article angle: \"The Shield\"**\nOpen with the contractor who left and is now competing against you. The non-compete you thought was protection is the clause that increased your misclassification risk. Body covers: state-by-state enforceability for ICs, income thresholds, the classification risk problem, trade secret alternative, international compensation requirements. Closer: AW builds the protective layer before the problem exists.\n\n**Working title candidates:**\n- \"Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements: What US Business Owners Need to Know Before They Hire\"\n- \"The Independent Contractor's Non-Compete: Protection or Liability?\"\n- \"How Non-Compete Agreements With Contractors Can Cost You Millions\"\n\n## PROVIDED CONTEXT — Research from SoT\n\n**Key data from research:**\n- 4 states with near-total bans: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma (non-competes void as matter of public policy)\n- Washington: IC threshold $317,147.09/year — significantly higher than employee threshold ($126,858.83)\n- DC: highest floor at $162,164\n- The \"Control Contradiction\": a non-compete dictates whom a contractor may work for after the relationship ends — this contradicts the fundamental requirement that an IC must be free to make their services available to the market. Courts and agencies view this as evidence of \"economic dependence\"\n- Chavez-DeRemer v. Medical Staffing of America: $9M judgment against a staffing company whose \"IC\" nurses were found to be employees. The non-compete was specifically cited as a \"red flag\" for control and economic dependence\n- FTC attempted ban: federal court struck down the FTC's non-compete rule in August 2024; no federal ban in place as of early 2026\n- For IC non-competes to be enforceable: must pass \"reasonableness test\" (geography, time, scope) AND protect a legitimate business interest (trade secrets, pricing models, customer lists)\n- Many courts now view 12-24 months with skepticism — 6-12 months increasingly standard for contractors\n- International: Germany requires 50% of last remuneration during non-compete period; France 30-50%; Italy 15-35%; UK prima facie void unless protecting a legitimate interest\n- Trade secret protection (DTSA/UTSA) is a stronger, narrower alternative — prevents use of stolen IP without restricting the person's ability to work\n- The Work Made for Hire doctrine has narrow categories — most creative/technical work (software, design, articles) doesn't qualify; backup assignment clauses needed\n- Termination: written agreements should specify notice periods (14-30 days standard), for-cause vs for-convenience, payment obligations, IP assignment\n- W-8 and 1042-S requirements for international contractors\n\n**Source types to cite:**\n- Epstein Becker Green, Littler Mendelson (law firm client alerts)\n- DOL, IRS official guidance\n- Deel, Remote (EOR platform operational guides)\n- Government sources: state labor departments, UK GOV.UK, EU employment law portals\n\n## SEO FRAMEWORK\n- URL slug: `/blog/independent-contractor-non-compete`\n- Word count target: 2,000-3,000 words\n- Primary keyword placement: H1, intro first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n- LSI keywords: \"independent contractor non-compete\", \"contractor non-compete agreement\", \"non-compete for contractors\", \"IC agreement restrictions\"\n- 2-5 outbound links to credible sources\n- 5-15 internal links to related AbroadWorks articles\n- Meta description: ≤156 chars, keyword + persuasive CTA\n- Paragraphs: 2-4 lines max, 4-6 sentences each\n- H2 sections: intro paragraph with transition sentence, body H3s, callout quote at end\n\n## YOUR TASK\nStart in PHASE 1. Ask Tiny (via the main session) your clarifying questions about audience, tone, key points to avoid, and confirm the current workflow phase before proposing H1 options.\n\nWait for responses before proceeding. Follow the 5-phase workflow strictly: H1 options → H2 structure → H3 ideas → Canvas (paragraph outline) → Draft.\n\nDo NOT generate a full draft until the canvas is explicitly approved.","label":"aw-article-1"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":72706,"output":1253,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73959,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775760033782}}
