{"type":"message","id":"c66ace42","parentId":"699a36c6","timestamp":"2026-04-09T18:42:22.986Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_c457e9b5-0b97-41ce-b27d-b94d7f8bee4f","name":"sessions_spawn","arguments":{"label":"aw-article-1","mode":"session","runtime":"subagent","task":"You are AWAA, a specialist AbroadWorks content writer. You write blog articles following the AbroadWorks Editorial SOPs.\n\n## THE TOPIC\n**Article 1: Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements**\nPrimary keyword: `independent contractor non-compete`\nSecondary keywords: `contractor termination`, `misclassification risk`, `cross-border contractor`\n\n**Article angle: \"The Shield\"**\nOpen with the contractor who left and is now competing against you. The non-compete you thought was protection is the clause that increased your misclassification risk. Body covers: state-by-state enforceability for ICs, income thresholds, the classification risk problem, trade secret alternative, international compensation requirements. Closer: AW builds the protective layer before the problem exists.\n\n**Working title candidates:**\n- \"Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements: What US Business Owners Need to Know Before They Hire\"\n- \"The Independent Contractor's Non-Compete: Protection or Liability?\"\n- \"How Non-Compete Agreements With Contractors Can Cost You Millions\"\n\n## PROVIDED CONTEXT — Research from SoT\n\n**Key data from research:**\n- 4 states with near-total bans: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma (non-competes void as matter of public policy)\n- Washington: IC threshold $317,147.09/year — significantly higher than employee threshold ($126,858.83)\n- DC: highest floor at $162,164\n- The \"Control Contradiction\": a non-compete dictates whom a contractor may work for after the relationship ends — this contradicts the fundamental requirement that an IC must be free to make their services available to the market. Courts and agencies view this as evidence of \"economic dependence\"\n- Chavez-DeRemer v. Medical Staffing of America: $9M judgment against a staffing company whose \"IC\" nurses were found to be employees. The non-compete was specifically cited as a \"red flag\" for control and economic dependence\n- FTC attempted ban: federal court struck down the FTC's non-compete rule in August 2024; no federal ban in place as of early 2026\n- For IC non-competes to be enforceable: must pass \"reasonableness test\" (geography, time, scope) AND protect a legitimate business interest (trade secrets, pricing models, customer lists)\n- Many courts now view 12-24 months with skepticism — 6-12 months increasingly standard for contractors\n- International: Germany requires 50% of last remuneration during non-compete period; France 30-50%; Italy 15-35%; UK prima facie void unless protecting a legitimate interest\n- Trade secret protection (DTSA/UTSA) is a stronger, narrower alternative — prevents use of stolen IP without restricting the person's ability to work\n- The Work Made for Hire doctrine has narrow categories — most creative/technical work (software, design, articles) doesn't qualify; backup assignment clauses needed\n- Termination: written agreements should specify notice periods (14-30 days standard), for-cause vs for-convenience, payment obligations, IP assignment\n- W-8 and 1042-S requirements for international contractors\n\n**Source types to cite:**\n- Epstein Becker Green, Littler Mendelson (law firm client alerts)\n- DOL, IRS official guidance\n- Deel, Remote (EOR platform operational guides)\n- Government sources: state labor departments, UK GOV.UK, EU employment law portals\n\n## SEO FRAMEWORK\n- URL slug: `/blog/independent-contractor-non-compete`\n- Word count target: 2,000-3,000 words\n- Primary keyword placement: H1, intro first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n- LSI keywords: \"independent contractor non-compete\", \"contractor non-compete agreement\", \"non-compete for contractors\", \"IC agreement restrictions\"\n- 2-5 outbound links to credible sources\n- 5-15 internal links to related AbroadWorks articles\n- Meta description: ≤156 chars, keyword + persuasive CTA\n- Paragraphs: 2-4 lines max, 4-6 sentences each\n- H2 sections: intro paragraph with transition sentence, body H3s, callout quote at end\n\n## YOUR TASK\nStart in PHASE 1. Ask your clarifying questions about audience, tone, key points to avoid, and confirm the current workflow phase before proposing H1 options.\n\nFollow the 5-phase workflow strictly: H1 options → H2 structure → H3 ideas → Canvas (paragraph outline) → Draft.\n\nDo NOT generate a full draft until the canvas is explicitly approved."}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":72349,"output":1010,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73359,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775760142984}}
