{"type":"message","id":"d8a07e7d","parentId":"28b59881","timestamp":"2026-04-09T19:11:46.393Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_b32deff2-66b7-4a9a-9676-afe1f29b0308","name":"sessions_spawn","arguments":{"label":"aw-article-1-full","mode":"run","runtime":"subagent","task":"You are AWAA, a specialist AbroadWorks content writer. You write blog articles following the AbroadWorks Editorial SOPs.\n\n## APPROVED H1\n**\"Independent Contractor Non-Compete: What It Actually Covers (and What It Doesn't)\"**\nPrimary keyword (EXACT, verbatim in H1): `independent contractor non-compete`\n\n## THE TOPIC\n**Article 1: Independent Contractor Non-Compete Agreements**\nPrimary keyword: `independent contractor non-compete`\nSecondary keywords: `contractor non-compete agreement`, `non-compete for contractors`, `IC agreement restrictions`, `contractor misclassification`, `independent contractor agreement`\n\n**Audience:** Micro-business owners (1-10 person companies) who hire or are considering hiring independent contractors. Most don't have formal agreements. Most don't know what a non-compete actually covers vs. what it leaves unprotected.\n\n**Angle:** Educational utility — \"here's what the non-compete actually does, why it might not protect you the way you think, and what to do instead.\" Earns the AW closer because the reader finishes knowing more than when they started, then understands why managed protection is worth it.\n\n**Tone:** Clear, direct, no jargon. Micro-business owners — not enterprise legal departments.\n\n## PROVIDED CONTEXT — Research from SoT\n\n**Key data:**\n- 4 states with near-total bans: California, Minnesota, North Dakota, Oklahoma — void as matter of public policy for ICs\n- Washington IC threshold: $317,147.09/year (vs employee threshold $126,858.83)\n- DC floor: $162,164\n- The \"Control Contradiction\": a non-compete dictates whom a contractor may work for after the relationship ends — courts view this as evidence of \"economic dependence\" and potential misclassification\n- *Chavez-DeRemer v. Medical Staffing of America*: $9M judgment, non-compete cited as misclassification red flag\n- FTC attempted ban: struck down August 2024, no federal ban in place\n- International: Germany requires 50% of last remuneration; France 30-50%; Italy 15-35%; UK prima facie void unless protecting legitimate interest\n- Trade secret protection (DTSA/UTSA) — stronger, narrower; protects IP without restricting the person's ability to work\n- Work Made for Hire: narrow categories (shorthand, contribution to collective work, compilation, instructional text); most creative/technical work needs backup assignment clauses\n- W-8 and 1042-S requirements for international contractors\n\n**Key framing to follow:**\nThe article should open with the question micro-business owners actually have: \"do I even need one?\" Then build the answer through: what it does → what it doesn't do → what actually protects you → AW as the managed layer.\n\n**SEO framework:**\n- URL slug: `/blog/independent-contractor-non-compete`\n- Word count target: 2,000-3,000 words\n- Primary keyword in: H1, intro first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n- Meta description: ≤156 chars, primary keyword, persuasive CTA\n- Paragraphs: 2-4 lines max, 4-6 sentences each\n- H2 sections: intro paragraph with transition sentence, body H3s, callout quote at end\n- 3 FAQs at conclusion — must be different from body content (operational anxieties, not repeated figures)\n- Internal links: link to at least 3 related AbroadWorks articles\n\n## YOUR TASK\n\nRun the full 5-phase workflow from PHASE 2 (H2 structure) through PHASE 5 (draft completion) without stopping for approval. The main session will review at the end.\n\n**PHASE 2 — H2 Structure:**\nPropose H2 structure following the Problem → Agitation → Solution flow:\n- H2 #1: What an independent contractor non-compete actually does\n- H2 #2: When it protects you vs when it leaves you exposed\n- H2 #3: What courts and state laws have decided about non-competes with ICs\n- H2 #4: What actually protects you when a contractor leaves\n- H2 #5: How to get the protection you need without the liability\n\n**PHASE 3 — H3 Sub-headings:**\nFor each H2, propose at least 3 H3 sub-sections with main ideas. Each H3 must hold a distinct, independent point.\n\n**PHASE 4 — Paragraph Canvas:**\nExpand the H3 structure into paragraph-level ideas. Every paragraph: main idea + supporting point. Follow 2x4-6 rule: exactly 2 paragraphs per H3, 4-6 sentences each. Every paragraph (except first in section) leads with transition word.\n\n**PHASE 5 — Full Draft:**\nWrite the complete article following all SOP requirements:\n- H1 exact match keyword\n- Introduction follows suspend-and-pivot model (acknowledge the appeal of non-competes, hint at the problem, don't give the solution away early)\n- All H2 intro paragraphs with transition sentences\n- All H3 sections: exactly 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences each\n- Callout quotes at end of every H2 section\n- Natural keyword integration — keywords in H1, first paragraph, at least one H2, conclusion\n- Math shown for all figures\n- All URLs from source documents (no generated URLs)\n- 3 FAQs at end (operational concerns, not repeated figures from body)\n- Final CTA positions AbroadWorks as the managed solution\n\n## EVALUATE YOUR OWN OUTPUT\nBefore submitting the final draft, run through the evaluation checklist:\n- [ ] H1 contains exact primary keyword \"independent contractor non-compete\"\n- [ ] No self-references\n- [ ] 1,800-2,500 words\n- [ ] No em-dashes or en-dashes\n- [ ] Bold only in headings and callout quotes (never in body text)\n- [ ] Every H3: 2 paragraphs, 4-6 sentences\n- [ ] Every paragraph (except first): leads with transition word\n- [ ] Every H2: intro paragraph + transition sentence + callout quote\n- [ ] 3 FAQs at end, no repeated math/figures from body\n- [ ] Math shown for all figures\n- [ ] No \"internal knowledge\" language\n- [ ] No banned terms\n\nComplete all phases. Deliver the final draft. Await evaluation from main session."}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":75979,"output":1556,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":77535,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775761906383}}
{"type":"message","id":"cb55b24c","parentId":"d8a07e7d","timestamp":"2026-04-09T19:11:47.462Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_b32deff2-66b7-4a9a-9676-afe1f29b0308","toolName":"sessions_spawn","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"accepted\",\n  \"childSessionKey\": \"agent:main:subagent:b72c5fcd-43e3-499b-8bdb-8999aaf6c18e\",\n  \"runId\": \"52eaaf31-035a-49a0-aac5-c1f01696d6a9\",\n  \"mode\": \"run\",\n  \"note\": \"Auto-announce is push-based. After spawning children, do NOT call sessions_list, sessions_history, exec sleep, or any polling tool. Wait for completion events to arrive as user messages, track expected child session keys, and only send your final answer after ALL expected completions arrive. If a child completion event arrives AFTER your final answer, reply ONLY with NO_REPLY.\",\n  \"modelApplied\": true\n}"}],"details":{"status":"accepted","childSessionKey":"agent:main:subagent:b72c5fcd-43e3-499b-8bdb-8999aaf6c18e","runId":"52eaaf31-035a-49a0-aac5-c1f01696d6a9","mode":"run","note":"Auto-announce is push-based. After spawning children, do NOT call sessions_list, sessions_history, exec sleep, or any polling tool. Wait for completion events to arrive as user messages, track expected child session keys, and only send your final answer after ALL expected completions arrive. If a child completion event arrives AFTER your final answer, reply ONLY with NO_REPLY.","modelApplied":true},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775761907445}}
