{"type":"message","id":"6af9f3c4","parentId":"48093585","timestamp":"2026-04-09T21:38:37.296Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n[[reply_to_current]] Found it. The gateway **is** serving the Control UI on port 18789 — confirmed by SSH. Port 18789 is open and responding on all interfaces. The title is \"OpenClaw Control.\" That's the page you're hitting.\n\nThe difference between Control UI and webchat might just be a routing question in the gateway config. Both serve from the same root, but the Control UI might be redirecting to `/dashboard` while webchat serves at `/`.\n\n**The actual question:** In your browser on your local machine — when you go to `http://204.168.204.198:18789/` and you're logged in to your local Dawn — what happens? Do you see the Control UI (Dawn's own) or does it give you a prompt to log in? That tells us whether Dusk's gateway is challenge-based auth or session-based."}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":73544,"output":450,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73994,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775770717289}}
{"type":"message","id":"c38696e2","parentId":"6af9f3c4","timestamp":"2026-04-09T21:41:52.905Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 23:41 GMT+2] It takes me to a log-in page that asks for a gateway token and an optional password. I thought the token was ollama but apparently it's not or there is an error: control ui requires device identity (use HTTPS or localhost secure context)"}],"timestamp":1775770912865}}
{"type":"message","id":"114f848d","parentId":"c38696e2","timestamp":"2026-04-09T21:42:03.830Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n[[reply_to_current]] That's the actual problem. Not an auth issue at all — it's a **secure context requirement**. OpenClaw's Control UI is refusing to load because you're accessing it over HTTP (not HTTPS) from a non-localhost origin. The browser itself is blocking it before any token authentication happens.\n\nThe error: *\"control ui requires device identity (use HTTPS or localhost secure context)\"*\n\nThis is a gateway security setting. Options to fix:\n\n**Option 1 — HTTPS on Dusk (cleanest):**\nGenerate a self-signed certificate on Dusk, configure the gateway to use it. Then access via `https://204.168.204.198:18789/`. The browser will throw a cert warning the first time — you'd click through it once.\n\n**Option 2 — Localhost tunnel (what you already have):**\nSSH tunnel to Dusk, then go to `http://127.0.0.1:18789/` from within the tunnel. That's localhost, so it passes the secure context check. This is the fastest fix — no config changes needed on Dusk.\n\n**Option 3 — Disable the secure context requirement:**\nChange the gateway config on Dusk to not require device identity. Insecure for production, fine for a VPS with a token.\n\n**My recommendation:** Option 2 — you already have the SSH access set up. Point your browser to `http://127.0.0.1:18789/` through the tunnel. That should work immediately.\n\nWant me to show you the config change for Option 3 (making it accessible via HTTPS properly) once we're past this?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":73910,"output":575,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":74485,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775770923826}}
{"type":"message","id":"5fe2e70f","parentId":"114f848d","timestamp":"2026-04-09T21:44:19.681Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-04-09 23:43:42 GMT+2] WhatsApp gateway disconnected (status 503)\nSystem: [2026-04-09 23:43:47 GMT+2] WhatsApp gateway connected.\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 23:44 GMT+2] When you say insecure for production, what do you mean here? Also, what do you mean that I already have a local host tunnel? Remember the point is to be able to access dusk from anywhere and on other machines."}],"timestamp":1775771059658}}
{"type":"message","id":"613f5ddc","parentId":"5fe2e70f","timestamp":"2026-04-09T21:44:34.698Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\n[[reply_to_current]] Fair points. Let me correct both.\n\n**\"Insecure for production\" means:**\nThe connection between your browser and Dusk would be unencrypted HTTP. Anyone on the network between you and Dusk — your ISP, wifi operators, etc. — could theoretically intercept the gateway token as it travels. The token is short and not designed to be exposed on an open HTTP port to the whole internet. That's fine on a trusted private network, but risky over public internet.\n\n**\"Localhost tunnel\" — what I meant:**\nThe SSH tunnel (`ssh -N -L 18789:127.0.0.1:18789 Tiny4Lurv@204.168.204.198`) only tunnels port 18789 to *your local machine*. It's not a general remote access solution. It's a one-machine workaround.\n\n**What you actually need for \"from anywhere\":**\nThe right production approach is a reverse proxy in front of the gateway. Something like:\n\n```\nBrowser → HTTPS (port 443) → nginx/caddy on Dusk → HTTP to gateway (port 18789)\n```\n\nnginx handles the HTTPS (with a self-signed or Let's Encrypt cert), proxies to the gateway, and the gateway sees a secure localhost connection. This is the standard way to expose a web service securely on a VPS.\n\n**The quick path forward:**\n1. Install nginx or Caddy on Dusk (takes minutes)\n2. Get a self-signed cert or use Let's Encrypt (free, automated)\n3. Proxy HTTPS port 443 to port 18789\n4. Access from anywhere at `https://204.168.204.198/` — browser will warn about the cert once, then it's fine\n\nThat also means the AntiGravity webapp can live on the same VPS, on the same domain, with the same HTTPS wrapper. One secure deployment.\n\nWant me to walk you through setting that up on Dusk?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":74510,"output":861,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75371,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775771074690}}
{"type":"message","id":"f3e46df2","parentId":"613f5ddc","timestamp":"2026-04-09T21:46:41.500Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-04-09 23:46 GMT+2] Can you just set it up and make sure to take extensive notes that are saved on the OneDrive backup folder you created for yourself?"}],"timestamp":1775771201490}}
